Food debt due to European inflation
The main reason for the rise in inflation in the euro area is the rapid rise in food prices.
In the 13 countries of the Eurozone, inflation was higher than expected in November - after 2.6 percent in October, an annual inflation rate of 3.1 percent was recorded, as reported by the EU Statistical Office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts are based on only 3 percent, Bloomberg reported.
In contrast to the American, British and Canadian central bank, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not reduced the Leitzinsin. In its opinion, the reduction in interest rates would favour the rise in raw material prices and the slight fall in unemployment to create a spiral of inflation.
The ECB aims to keep the inflation rate below two per cent, or at least close to the two per cent mark.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in the zwickmühle: inflation had to be "agreed" in order to rule out the need for further action.
At 3.3 percent, the inflation rate reached a 12-year record high in Germany in November; in Spain, the rate rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
The rise in inflation in the euro area was due to the rise in food and energy prices.
The MATIF wheat quotations increased by 88 percent, and the price for soybeans has also reached a record high since 1973.
There was also a significant cost in 2007 for food oil and dairy products.
The world market price for crude oil rose by 52 percent this year - last month the price per barrel of black gold reached nearly 100 US dollars.
According to the ECB, inflation will rise from 2.1 to 2.5 percent in 2008 but is expected to fall to 1.9 percent in 2009.
For the next 3-4 months, analysts estimate a 3-percent inflation rate, but the annual average rate is 2.1 percent.
For 2008, experts expect the ECB to reduce interest twice.
