In many places, disinfectants are saved
This year, more than a thousand infections have been recorded in hospitals due to improper handling of antibiotics.
The hygiene conditions in the hospitals, the overcrowding of beds, the overcrowding of staff - all factors that do not exactly contribute to the containment of infections, according to the leading doctor of the National Epidemiology Centre.
In many places the disinfectants are also saved.
In the traumatology department of the János hospital an MRSA infection was recently diagnosed.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was found in a male patient who was hospitalized after a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year there was already a similar infection here.
The injured person of a serious car accident was released from the hospital, but a little later the man had to return with an MRSA infection. Since then, an important operation has not been performed due to the bacterium still in the patient’s body.
Until December 10 of this year, multi-resistant pathogen-induced infections to the National Nosocomomialis Surveillance System were reported from hospitals in 1094, according to Karolina Böröcz, the lead doctor of the National Epidemiology Center.
So many infections caused by multi-resistant pathogens have been recorded in hospitals with certainty, but the dark figure is likely to be higher.
About two thirds of infections (683 cases) were caused by MRSA, the Staphylococcus aureus resistant to methicillin oxacillin.
The Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria carries about one third of the people in their nose without causing any disease.
SA-related infections (such as sore throat, almond inflammation, inflammation of the skin or wounds) usually respond well to antibiotics, they are well curable.
However, if the substances are used too high or inappropriately, they are caused by the well-responsive bacteria, antibiotics-resistant, which spread rapidly in hospitals under appropriate conditions.
Especially in patients with weakened, or permanently malfunctioning immune system, but also in the elderly, or patients with low body weight, these bacteria can cause severe infections, such as wound infection or blood poisoning, i.e. sepsis.
According to the medical director of the János Hospital, MRSA infection is nothing special, such incidents are part of the everyday routine of the hospital.
One should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, Tibor Nyulasi warned - MRSA just doesn't exist where it's not being searched.
Resistant to Antibiotics
"These patients are isolated, the caregiver wears rubber gloves and masks in the supply, and we have the antibiotics necessary for the treatment" - says Tibor Nyulasi.
Although patients are being examined for MRSA at their hospitalisation, an infection cannot always be avoided.
Samples taken too rarely
The majority of infections caused by MRSA in hospitals would be avoidable, but the current conditions and circumstances would be unfavourable for the inhibition of the emergence or spread of the multi-resistant pathogen, says Karolina Böröcz.
After this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and old-age homes, the hospitals should examine the patients who have been hospitalised and immediately isolate MRSA-infected patients.
However, microbiological sampling is not practised so often in Hungarian hospitals.
Not least because there are no grants for this investigation from the State Health Insurance Fund.
Most of the cases would therefore only come to light when the patient already has a notable MRSA infection, according to the medical director of the epidemiology center.
There are strict recommendations from the European Union on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine, but there are also guidelines in Hungary for the treatment of certain infections and diseases.
Antibiotic therapies should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests are necessary to prevent resistance to the drug, but this directive is not always complied with by hospitals.
Among the outpatients, or patients in primary care, microbiological samples are even rarer, says Karolina Böröcz.
Saved in the disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA is most often transferred from one patient to the other by the caregiver.
This is precisely why hand washing, or wearing gloves and masks, is of great importance, but there are also considerable shortcomings in hospitals in this area.
MRSA is transmitted by droplet infection or contact, but in local hospitals there is not always the possibility to isolate the infected patient.
The rooms are often crowded, the beds are scarcely lined, although there should be a distance of at least 1.5 meters between them from an epidemiological point of view.
As Karolina Böröcz further notes, unfortunately, even in the less well-off hospitals, there are few caregivers, many patients - all factors that actually favour the development of infections.
Such infections are proven to be far less common there, or the further spread of the pathogen can be stopped where these protective measures are observed, says Karolina Böröcz.
Government programme against MRSA
Getting MRSA infections into control causes the health insurances enormous costs, so they are fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the prevention of MRSA, or its containment, was recorded in the government programme.
After first signs, the program is successful - as published data prove, the trend of MRSA infections in England is decreasing.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention (ECDC) has identified the prevention of the development of multi-resistant pathogens (including MRSA) and the prevention of infections in hospitals as one of its priorities.
