Fodor and the six Hungarian percentages
As Environment Minister Gábor Fodor announced, the expert meetings will end on Tuesday, and the debate on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue on Wednesday after the official opening.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries discuss the Bali roadmap, which sets out emission reduction measures for the period after 2012, i.e. after the end of the Kyoto Protocol.
There is currently a heated debate between industrial and developing countries.
The US has already signaled that they do not want to negotiate specific figures, but they would be willing to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 25-40 percent by 2020 compared to 1990.
The other major issue of the conference is whether the industrialised countries are willing to support developing countries both financially and technologically in addition to reducing emissions.
An agreement was also reached on the support of developing countries.
The Kyoto Adjustment Fund is to be managed by a 16-member Council, which is expected to be part of the UN Global Environmental Facility (GEF), as shown in the 'Piac és Profit'.
Six percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, Environment Minister Gábor Fodor supports the EU's efforts to maintain its pioneering role in global climate change measures and to reach a new international agreement by 2009.
The Minister said that the EU would reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 20% by 2020 (as measured by 1990 values), regardless of whether the "agreement after 2012" was successful or not. The Union would even be willing to use itself for a 30% reduction, provided that other major industrialised countries in the world, or developing countries, are also willing to fulfil their obligations according to their strengths and responsibilities.
Gábor Fodor stressed that the objective of the countries that had joined the Kyoto Protocol in 1997 was a reduction of only 5.2%, whereas the EU had already committed itself to a reduction of 8% with its 15 Member States.
The target for Hungary is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6% compared to 1985-87 - a target that the country will meet, as can be seen in the Ministry of the Environment's press release.
The commitment is high in Bali - after all, the long-term international climate agreement must be completed within two years, otherwise it would certainly not enter into force until after 2012. In this case, the reduction project set out in the Kyoto Protocol would not follow a renewed international emission reduction system, the importance of which has also been highlighted in its latest report by the IPCC, the UN Scientific Committee on Climate Change, which is awarded the Nobel Peace Prize.
This would delay the emission reduction, and the increase in the average temperature of the earth by more than 2°C would be inevitable, which, according to scientists, would result in extremely serious and irreparable consequences.
British army advertises on YouTube
Units of the British Army have published recordings of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan to increase popularity on the video portal.
First, the British Air Force (RAF) discovered YouTube for itself: Since March 2006, special units stationed in Afghanistan have been uploading videos of operations conducted against the Taliban, reports the BBC.
The miniature cameras, which are mounted on helmets, are controlled at the Air Force Base in Kandahar and then sent to London, where they are placed on the Internet.
Political message inevitable
Air Force soldiers have already contributed 139 such recordings, their "channel" has been viewed more than 75,000 times.
The British Ministry of Defence was registered under "defenceheadquarters" in spring 2007 to publish videos on Iraqi and Afghan operations, but also the British Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Commonwealth Office) and the International Peace Forces (MNFIs) stationed in Iraq have their own YouTube channels.
Use in Afghanistan
Originally, the Air Force has published the videos with the aim of recruiting soldiers, and, as the Ministry of Defence says, the contributions also serve the purpose of informing the population about the actual objectives of foreign operations.
According to defense expert Gordon Mackenzie to the BBC, this kind of published propaganda is almost free of charge compared to conventional television advertising, but these videos always carry a certain degree of political message in themselves, as they confirm the existence of the military measures decided by the government in their own way.
Americans advertise with game
But the army must also fight against amateur shots that create it alongside the carefully processed, censored shots into the net - such as those that show the death of the soldiers: In the somewhat hypocritical, "official" propaganda films, it is spoken of at most the losses, but the bloody sides of the war are not shown.
By the way, many videos of the war scenes in Iraq and Afghanistan have already been loaded into the platform, but the British have only recently discovered this "gift".
The Americans, however, advertise in a slightly different way, namely with the free downloadable shooting game "America's Army", in which the player can slip into the soldier's skin as part of a more or less life-threatening simulation.
