Holidays are not everywhere holidays
In Hungary, holidays are regulated by law, so that the practice of redeploying the working days around the holidays has now established itself, but the coming year provides us with less such days.
In the EU and in America, too, something else is referred to as "the holiday".
The Hungarian legal system distinguishes between public holidays and working days.
Unemployed days are mostly church holidays, or are related to important historical events.
For example, we are also celebrating New Year: both the last day of the old year and the first day of the new year are days without work - the latter alone, so that the New Year's celebrations can rest.
All year round we have a total of fourteen holidays.
The public holidays are the 15th of March, which commemorates the revolution of 1848, and the 23rd of October, the anniversary of the revolution of 1956.
On August 20th the foundation of the state, on May 1st the work is celebrated, on November 1st and 2nd we commemorate our dead.
In addition, there are two holidays each at Easter, Pentecost, and Christmas.
Since our state, national or religious holidays rarely fall on a weekend, the practice of "working day shift" has proven itself in cases where we would only work one day before or after the holiday.
The price of the extended weekends, however, is that we have to work very well on the Saturdays before, or go to school.
When this day, which falls before or after the holiday, is finally to be worked out, the Minister of Labour has been laying down a separate regulation for many years.
The legislation applies equally to all employers, public servants and civil servants.
Only companies and institutions in which the operation is continued without interruption, i.e. also on the holidays, are excluded.
This year the working order is only mixed up by the holidays at the end of the year: from 24 December, life will remain in this country, as most people take the time off for the days between Christmas and New Year's Eve, or the special holiday for it.
In the next year, more holidays fall into the middle of the week, or the end of the week, so that there will be fewer redeployments in the working days than this year.
The calendar is first placed "on the head" around the day of work, so that people can stay at home for four days.
Saturday, April 26 will be a working day so that Friday, May 2 can be a day of rest.
The second re-disposal is linked to the holiday on October 23rd: on Saturday, October 18th you will have to finish the Friday, October 24th.
The end of the year will, however, be the sign of the holidays after December 24th, even if New Year's Eve falls on a Wednesday.
