A heavy reminder
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which document the fates of 17,5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are now freely accessible.
The 47 million documents of the archive, which are housed in Bad Arolsen for a total length of 27 km, could not be seen until now, unless with a humanitarian intention, that is, individually and name-based, i.e. at the request of a former victim or his family.
The eleven States entrusted with their administration - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to make them available to researchers and historians.
After the ratification process of this Decision has been completed, the opening has been valid since yesterday.
Key information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will make it possible to conduct research, especially on the deportation of prisoners, the inmates of the concentration camps and the health status of the forced workers, explains Reto Meistern, head of this archive, which is managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (CICR).
Until recently, several states, including Germany, have been opposed to making these documents related to their names available to the public because of the delicate nature of certain information.
Like the alleged homosexuality or the mental disability of some deportation victims.
The inmates' lists of concentration camps or the warrants issued by the Gestapo had been gathered after the war for a practical reason: to find civilians who had been deported or forced to work, and possibly to provide them with evidence of their arrest, thus paving the way for their compensation.
Even today, more than 300 permanent employees are processing tens of thousands of personal requests in Bad Arolsen.
Nevertheless, a part of the scientific community shows only a limited interest in accessing Bad Arolsen.
One cannot expect anything fundamentally new in these documents, said Pr. Wolfgang Benz, Head of the Research Center for Anti-Semitism at the Technical University of Berlin, 2006.
