In addition to the modernisation of the financial markets, the MIFID, which is revising the Securities Services Regulation, is pursuing an improvement in investor protection, an increase in the control requirement of the Spanish Securities Commission (CNMV) and the promotion of cooperation between the various control authorities of the European Union.
The new Directive makes it possible to provide both specialised companies and natural or legal persons with financial advice and also contributes to the creation of new financial services companies (ESIS), the consultancy companies that are merging with the investment and brokerage companies of securities.
In addition, it extends the number of systems for the execution of financial transactions so that the regulated circulation markets are added to the multilateral securities trading systems and to the systems for the internationalisation of trading orders, which would eventually enter into competition with the current economic operators.
The law obliges investment companies to disclose the focus of their corporate profile, confrontation and forms of dealing with risks on the market and to register all projects carried out in order to facilitate the control task of the CNMV.
