New concerns about natural gas dispute between Russia and Ukraine
A new price dispute is emerging between Ukraine and Russia, increasing the risk that Russian exports of fuel to Western Europe will be affected.
The majority of Russian exports of natural gas to the European Union (EU) are managed by Ukraine and every dispute between the two nations is observed very closely.
Kiev has warned that if Moscow increases the price it has to pay for the natural gas, it will charge higher transit fees from Russia.
An earlier conflict between the two states last year reduced deliveries to the EU countries.
The recent conflict between Kiev and Moscow takes place at a time when the Ukrainian government and the Russian state gas monopoly Gazprom are trying to reach an agreement on how much Ukraine has to pay for Russian natural gas in 2008.
According to Gazprom, Ukraine has to be more calculated as the Group has agreed to pay up to 50% additional for natural gas from neighbouring Turkmenistan.
Analysts say that this could mean that Ukraine has to pay 40% more for Gazprom imports.
"It is important for us to use our arguments as one of the most important gas transit states in talks," said Ukraine's Minister of Economic Affairs Anatoli Kinakh of Reuters News Agency.
"The changing gas prices should undoubtedly be linked to our arguments regarding the amount of transit fees [to Western Europe] on Ukraine."
In the last major natural gas dispute between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006, Gazprom reduced deliveries to Ukraine.
This led to a fall in exports to Western Europe, which drastically increased prices.
Russian gas accounts for one quarter of the European Union's supply.
Russia has the largest gas deposits worldwide, but much of it remains underdeveloped.
The result is that Gazprom complements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other Central Asian former Soviet nations.
NHS "must control foreign workers"
The Scottish State Health Service must improve the controls of the pre-criminal registers for workers from outside Europe, said a member of the control body.
The recommendation of the chief financial controller Robert Black came after a foreign doctor in Scotland was brought together with the attack on Glasgow Airport in June.
Black also expressed concern that the Scottish State Health Service did not have precise ideas about the number of its foreign employees.
However, his report pointed out that other important controls were carried out correctly in a sample of five health authorities.
The main financial controller investigated personnel recruited outside the countries of the European Economic Area as a result of the attack on Glasgow Airport.
Bilal Abdullah, 28, an Iraqi doctor at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after an off-road car was driven through the doors of the main airport terminal.
He was one of three doctors who appeared in a video transmission in October in Old Bailey and was charged with the suspected car bombing in the UK.
It is expected that the State Health Service will carry out checks in advance of the employment of foreign employees to ensure that they have the necessary qualifications, experience and authorizations to work in the United Kingdom.
Although the health authorities use Disclosure Scotland to check criminal records, the Agency does not have the competence to obtain this information outside the UK.
The main reviewer's report now states, in addition to other recommendations, that the Management Board should adopt guidelines on criminal record collection that help employers in controls in different countries.
"Although we have found evidence of these checks in some personnel documents, they have not been carried out routinely." the report noted.
Black said that the Scottish health authorities would closely follow their pre-employment guidelines, but added: "Our report identifies areas in which the system can be improved to ensure that accurate information is available on the number of foreign health professionals."
BMA Scotland President Dr. Peter Terry said it was "extremely unlikely" that investigations prior to hiring potential NHS employees would identify people who could commit future terrorist attacks.
"The report says that current pre-employment tests of the NHS Scotland are working well and it is not clear what added value the recommendations will provide," he said.
The Scottish health authorities say they currently have 1,161 foreign employees, the vast majority of whom are doctors and nurses.
However, the financial controller warned that the number was likely to be higher, also because the directors had problems identifying those employees who were on leave for an indefinite period.
The investigation continued to show that established control procedures have been largely complied with by the NHS authorities in Ayrshire, Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian.
These include passport, work permit and qualification checks.
the Scottish Government is currently reviewing its policies and guidelines for pre-employment checks for foreign personnel in the NHS.
