Venus is the hellish twin of the earth
Venus, despite its anti-lifelike atmosphere on earth, is more similar to that previously thought: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind whirlwinds on the Poles, as they also occur on earth in winter.
For almost three decades, scientists have suspected that Venus is flashing.
Now the European probe "Venus Express" has provided evidence - it detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: The flashes on Venus shoot at an altitude of about 56 kilometers from cloud to cloud, reports Christopher Russel from the University of California in Los Angeles in the science magazine "Nature".
According to the famous "Ursuppen theory", lightning has created life on earth: thunderstorms are said to have triggered reactions in the ocean that led to the formation of amino acids, the building blocks of life.
Not so on Venus: "If there was ever life there, it must have been in the very early history," explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there is hardly anything alive on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on earth, it sometimes has temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be the devil twin of the earth, but it is a twin," said Russel.
Why the Venus, which is so similar to the Earth in mass and size, has taken on such a completely different development, is the fundamental question of the Esa mission.
The launch of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was a milestone in Venus research, as since the early 1990s no longer had a probe specifically on the way to exploring this planet.
According to the researchers, the latest research results, which are now presented in several "nature" articles, underline not only the uniqueness of Venus within the solar system.
"They also show that the fellowships of our neighboring planet with the earth are greater than initially assumed," the Esa announces.
In addition to the already known whirlwind at the North Pole, the researchers also found a cloud strudel at the South Pole, which rotates much faster.
The phenomenon reminds of air currents on the earthly winter hemisphere, writes a research team around Giuseppe Piccioni from the Italian Istituto di Astrofisica Spatiale e Fisica Cosmica.
The second inner planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the earth and is almost the same size with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers.
The planet, also known as morning or evening star, orbits around the sun in just under 225 days.
But it turns much slower about itself: a Venus Day takes 243 Earth days.
Although Venus is hardly reminiscent of the Earth with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, scientists assume that both planets have developed under very similar conditions.
Both gathered water that remained on earth in oceans but on which Venus was lost into space.
And while carbon dioxide is fixed on the earth in carbonate stones, it makes up most of the atmosphere on Venus.
