Currently, wooden boxes made in Sweden cast dark shadows on Warhol's catalogue of works.
Most of the twenty-four brollo boxes of "type Stockholm" listed there are forgery.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" had some months ago cast doubt on the authenticity of Andy Warhol's Brillo boxes in 1968, internal research at Moderna Museet in Stockholm has now reached a sobering conclusion: The six "Brillo boxes", which the former museum director Pontus Hultén has given to Moderna Museet in 1995, are copies - and probably the majority of the approximately one hundred other Brillo boxes from the "Type Stockholm", which are in circulation on the international art market.
The prehistory is shattered, a confusing chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted wooden boxes based on the red-blue-white design of the cardboard box of the "Brillo" soap powder.
An exhibition of his works at the Moderna Museet 1968, with Warhol's consent, produced hundreds of Brillo boxes from cardboard: These were not from Warhol (for cost reasons) but were delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
It was not about works of art, but about their role models, just exhibition pieces.
At the same time, in 1968, Warhol probably granted permission to produce a few Brillo wooden caskets in Sweden, which were not exhibited in Moderna Museet.
Contemporary witnesses are now talking about about about fifteen crates, which were then properly introduced into the art and auction history as authorized original Andy-Warhol-Brillo boxes called "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have achieved more than $100,000 at auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary museum director Pontus Hultén later falsely claimed that it had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol had then left to him.
In fact, Hultén's 105 crates were only produced in Malmö in 1990 for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
At that time Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, Chief Conservator at Moderna Museet, has also examined three of the Swedish private property in addition to the six museum's own Brillo-Boxes, two of which were manufactured in Stockholm in 1968: their press panel was first founded and smeared, then white oil paint was applied with a brush.
The structure of the 1990 copies, on the other hand, reveals that the paint was applied directly to the press panel without a primer roll - and this is not about oil, but about acrylic paint.
"These crates were not authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," says the director of Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve, saying: "If the Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board in New York does not reach a different conclusion, the Moderna Museet will classify the six crates in its collection as copies/exhibition material."
